  <h>air</h>
  <p><g>air</g>
    <en>on, upon</en> is the (usually non-leniting) superessive <a href="?xx=prepositions/prepositions"
      >preposition</a>.</p>
  <!-- ROM – Note that air can lenite in some expressions which describe a state e.g. air chrith, air bhoil. Also involving parts of the body e.g. beir air chasan; cf also air bharr 'on top', etc. Worth adding a note. -->
  <section>
    <h>forms</h>
    <section id="indefinite">
      <h>indefinite</h>
      <p>The default form of the superessive preposition is simply <g>air</g> – <ul>
          <li><m>air</m> bòrd <en>on a table</en></li>
          <li><m>air</m> aibhnichean <en>on rivers</en></li>
          <li><m>air</m> Neaptun <en>on Neptune</en></li>
          <li><m>air</m> trì leapannan <en>on three beds</en></li>
        </ul></p>
    </section>
    <section id="definite">
      <h>definite</h>
      <p>Unlike with some other prepositions, there is no special form of <g>air</g> used before the
        definite article – <ul>
          <li><m>air an</m> talamh <en>on the ground</en></li>
          <li><m>air a’</m> bhòrd <en>on the table</en></li>
          <li><m>air na h-</m>itealain <en>on the airplanes</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>Moreover, there are no fused forms with <g>air</g> and a<!--<a
          href="?xx=nouns/possessive_determiners">possessive determiner</a>-->
          possessive determiner – <ul>
          <li><m>air mo</m> cheann <en>on my head</en></li>
          <li><m>air do</m> bhòrd <en>on your table</en></li>
            <!-- ROM – But we do get orra for air do < air dho -->
          <li><m>air a h-</m>ùbhlan <en>on her apples</en></li>
          <li><m>air a</m> chois <en>on his foot</en></li>
          <li><m>air ar</m> sgeilpean <en>on our shelves</en></li>
          <li><m>air ur</m> coin <en>on your dogs</en></li>
          <li><m>air an</m> taighean <en>on their houses</en></li>
          <li><m>air am</m> fearann <en>on their land</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </section>
    <section id="pronouns">
      <h>prepositional pronouns</h>
      <p>Conjugated prepositions are used in place of <bad>air mi</bad>, <bad>air thu</bad>, ... ,
          <bad>air iad</bad> – <ul>
          <li><m>orm</m>
            <en>on me</en></li>
          <li><m>ort</m>
            <en>on you</en></li>
          <li><m>oirre</m>
            <en>on her/it</en></li>
          <li><m>air</m>
            <en>on him/it</en></li>
          <li><m>oirnn</m>
            <en>on us</en></li>
          <li><m>oirbh</m>
            <en>on you</en></li>
          <li><m>orra</m>
            <en>on them</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>There are also emphatic forms (cf. <bad>air mise</bad>, <bad>air thusa</bad>, ... ,
          <bad>air iadsan</bad>) – <ul>
          <li><m>ormsa</m>
            <en>on <emph>me</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>ortsa</m>
            <en>on <emph>you</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>oirrese</m>
            <en>on <emph>her/it</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>airsan</m>
            <en>on <emph>him/it</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>oirnne</m>
            <en>on <emph>us</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>oirbhse</m>
            <en>on <emph>you</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>orrasan</m>
            <en>on <emph>them</emph></en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>Note that the form <g>airsan</g> breaks the ‘slender-to-slender, broad-to-broad’ spelling
        rule, and hence is sometimes found written with a hyphen – <g>air-san</g>.</p>
      <p>Finally, there are also reflexive forms (cf. <bad>air mi fhìn</bad>, <bad>air thu
          fhèin</bad>, ... <bad>air iad fhèin</bad>) – <ul>
          <li><m>orm fhèin / fhìn</m>
            <en>on myself</en></li>
            <!-- ROM: Note that fhein (grace accent) is sound in some dialects with 1 sg and pl. -bh + fhein is often pronounced pein -->
            <!-- WL: Cox (2017: 219) notes fhìn is also sometimes used with i -->
          <li><m>ort fhèin</m>
            <en>on yourself</en></li>
          <li><m>oirre fhèin</m>
            <en>on herself/itself</en></li>
          <li><m>air fhèin</m>
            <en>on himself/itself</en></li>
          <li><m>oirnn fhèin / fhìn</m>
            <en>on ourselves</en></li>
          <li><m>oirbh fhèin</m>
            <en>on yourself</en></li>
          <li><m>orra fhèin</m>
            <en>on themselves</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>Note that <g>-bh</g> + <g>fhèin</g> is often pronounced <g>pèin</g> in <g>oirbh fhèin</g>.</p>
    </section>
  </section>

