  <section>
    <h>uses</h>
    <section id="uses-pred">
      <h>predicate</h>
      <p>One common use of the preposition <g>air</g> is to introduce the predicate of the verb <a
          href="?gd=bi"><g>bi</g></a> – <ul>
          <li><m>Tha</m> Seònaid <m>air</m> an taigh-sholais. <en>Janet is on the
            lighthouse</en>.</li>
          <li><m>Tha</m> falt fada <m>orm</m>. <en>I have long hair.</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>Some specific subtypes of predicate relation are described in the following sections.</p>

      <section id="uses-pred-loc">
        <h>locative</h>
        <p>Some examples – <ul>
            <li>pedagogical examples – <xl id="uses-pred-loc-pedag">
                <li>
                  <gd>Tha [an salann] shuas <m>air an sgeilp sin</m>.</gd>
                  <tr>[The salt] is up there on that shelf.</tr>
                  <ref text="609">td. 35</ref>
                </li>
              </xl></li>
          </ul></p>
      </section>
      <section id="uses-pred-clothing">
        <h>clothing</h>
        <p>Some examples – <ul>
            <li>pedagogical examples – <xl id="uses-pred-clothing-pedag">
                <li>
                  <gd>Tha còta snog oirre. Tha peitean air Iain. Tha brògan àrda orra. Tha ad
                    air.</gd>
                  <tr>She is wearing a nice coat. John is wearing a jumper. They are wearing boots.
                    He is wearing a hat.</tr>
                  <ref text="609">td. 64</ref>
                </li>
              </xl>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </section>
      <section id="uses-pred-naming">
        <h>naming</h>
        <p>Some examples – <ul>
            <li>pedagogical examples – <xl id="uses-pred-naming-pedag">
                <li>
                  <gd>Dè an t-ainm a tha ort? / C’ ainm a tha ort? Is e Iain (an t-ainm) a tha
                    orm.</gd>
                  <tr>What is your name? John is my name.</tr>
                  <ref text="609">td. 64</ref>
                </li>
              </xl>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="uses-pred-affliction">
        <h>affliction</h>
        <p>Some examples – <ul>
            <li>pedagogical examples – <xl id="uses-pred-affliction-pedag">
                <li>
                  <gd>Tha an t-acras orm. Tha am pathadh ort. Tha an cnatan air. Tha an t-eagal
                    oirre. Tha cabhag oirnn.</gd>
                  <tr>I am hungry. You are thirsty. He has a cold. She is afraid. We are in a
                    hurry.</tr>
                  <ref text="609">td. 64</ref>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <gd>Tha an cadal orm agus is beag orm plèanaichean co-dhiù.</gd>
                  <tr>I am sleepy and I don’t like planes anyway.</tr>
                  <ref text="609">td. 66</ref>
                  <note>deps|complement|human|patient, uses|predicate|affliction|idiom</note>
                </li>
              </xl>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="uses-pred-retro">
        <h>retrospective (perfect) aspect</h>
        <p>When the preposition <g>air</g> governs an infinitive (verbal noun), it generally
          indicates <a href="?q=verbal_aspect">retrospective aspect</a>, similar in some ways to the
          English ‘perfect tenses’ – <ul>
            <li><m>Tha Raonaid air taigh a cheannach.</m>
              <en>Rachel has bought a house.</en></li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <section>
          <h>intransitive</h>
          <p>Basic pattern – <ul>
              <li><m>Tha Seumas air èirigh.</m>
                <en>James has risen.</en></li>
            </ul>
          </p>
          <p>Examples from dictionaries and grammars – <xl id="retro-intrans-dictionary">
              <li>
                <gd>Tha iad air falbh.</gd>
                <tr>They have gone.</tr>
                <ref text="605">td. 11</ref>
              </li>
              <li>
                <gd>Tha iad air tighinn dhachaigh.</gd>
                <tr>They have come home.</tr>
                <ref text="601">td. 22</ref>
              </li>
              <li>
                <gd>Bha Uilleam air tilleadh. / Bidh iad air a dhol a-mach. / Bhiodh Màiri air
                  seinn.</gd>
                <tr>William had returned. / They will have gone out. / Mary would have sung.</tr>
                <ref text="609">td. 158–9</ref>
              </li>
            </xl>
          </p>
        </section>
        <section>
          <h>transitive with inversion</h>
          <p>Basic pattern – <ul>
              <li><m>Tha Raonaid air na balaich a phògadh.</m>
                <en>Rachel has kissed the boys.</en></li>
            </ul>
          </p>
          <p>Note that the object noun is in the nominative case, rather than the dative, in this
            context – Tha Raonaid air <m>am balach</m> a phògadh. <en>Rachel has kissed the boy.</en></p>
          <p>Examples from dictionaries and grammars – <xl id="retro-inversion-dictionary">
              <li>
                <gd>Bha mi air an doras a dhùnadh.</gd>
                <tr>I had closed the door.</tr>
                <ref text="605">td. 11</ref>
              </li>
              <li>
                <gd>Tha Anna air an t-uisge a òl. / Bha Niall air Gàidhlig a ionnsachadh. / Bidh
                  Dàibhidh air an doras a pheantadh. / Bhiodh Calum air leabhar a cheannach. / Tha
                  Raibeart air an cù a bhiadhadh mar-thà. / Tha Anna air am borbair a
                  phàigheadh.</gd>
                <tr>Ann has drunk the water. / Neil has learnt Gaelic. / David will have painted the
                  door. / Calum would have bought a book. / Robert has fed the dog already. / Ann
                  has paid the hairdresser.</tr>
                <ref text="609">td. 158–9</ref>
                <note>Note blocking of dative case in first example here.</note>
              </li>
              <li>
                <gd>A bheil thu air an iuchair a bhriseadh?</gd>
                <tr>Have you broken the key?</tr>
                <ref text="601">td. 22</ref>
              </li>
            </xl>
          </p>
          <p>Examples from Gairm – <xl id="retro-inversion-gairm">
              <li>
                <gd>[...] ’Se glé bheag de chobhair a thug a’ Phàrlamaid a riamh do ’n Ghàidhlig no
                  do fhoghlum agus do litreachas na Gàidhlig. [...] Dé na rudan a dh’ fhaodadh sinn
                  iarraidh? [...] Chan eil an sin ach rud no dhà a dh’ fhaodamaid iarraidh. <m>Tha
                    Comunn nan Croitearan air nì de ’n t-seòrsa so iarraidh mar tha</m>, air a’
                  Bh.B.C. Thug sin togail inntinn dhuinn. Có a nis a chuireas fead chruaidh ann an
                  cluais Luchd an Ionmhais ann a Westminster?</gd>
                <tr>[...] The Parliament has given very little assistance ever to the Gaelic
                  language or to Gaelic education and literature. [...] What are the things that we
                  could demand? [...] Those are just a couple of things that we could demand. The
                  Crofters’ Society has demanded something of this kind already, on the BBC. That
                  has given us inspiration. Who now will put a hard whistle [?] in the ear of the
                  Finance People in Westminster?</tr>
                <ref text="400-46">td. 105, ‘Air an Spiris’</ref>
              </li>
            </xl>
          </p>
          <p>Other examples from modern usage – <xl id="retro-inversion-modern">
              <li>
                <gd>[...] B’ e Rob a b’ òige agus lean e an sgoil. Nuair a ràinig e an t-oilthigh
                  bha càch airson gun ionnsaicheadh e cunntasachd, a bhiodh feumail anns a’
                  mhalairt, ach ’s ann a bha ùidh-san ann an ealain. Dh’fhàg e an t-oilthigh agus
                  chaidh e do sgoil ealain. Bha cuibhreann aige bho athair a bha tuilleadh ’s gu
                  leòr airson fheumalachd ged a bha e dèidheil air a’ bhotal, agus cha robh e a’
                  dèanamh spàirn sam bith airson faighinn air adhart san t-saoghal. Bhiodh e a’
                  dèanamh sgrùdadh ealain do phàipear-naidheachd agus corra dhealbh, ach bha a
                  chaitheamh-beatha glè fhada bho ùpraid muinntir Thòmais, no ‘mafia’ Thòmais, mar a
                  chanadh e fhèin. Nuair a dh’innis e <m>gu robh e air nighean a thoirt a
                    dh’fhuireach còmhla ris</m>, thuirt Tòmas ri càch, [...] ’S ann an taigh
                  Aonghais a’ Bhàillidh – caraid a bha còmhla ris san sgoil – a bhiodh Rob a’
                  fuireach nuair a bhiodh e aig an taigh. <m>Bha muinntir Thòmais air an clachan
                    fhàgail o chionn fhada.</m> [...] </gd>
                <tr>[...] Rob was the youngest [in the family] and he stayed on at school. When he
                  reached the university the others wanted him to learn accountancy, which would be
                  useful in the business, but his interest was in art. He left the university and
                  went to an art school. He had an allowance from his father which more more than
                  enough for his needs even though he was fond of the bottle, and he was not making
                  any effort to get on in the world. He would be making art reviews for a newspaper
                  and some pictures, but his way of life was very far from the commotion of Thomas’
                  people, or Thomas’ ‘mafia’, as he would say himself. When he announced that he had
                  brought a girl to live with him, Thomas said to the others, [...] It was in Angus
                  of the Baillie’s house – a friend who was with him in the school – that Rob would
                  be staying when he would be at home. Thomàs’ [Rob’s father] people had left the
                  village long before. [...]</tr>
                <ref text="2">td. 5</ref>
              </li>
            </xl>
          </p>
        </section>
        <section>
          <h>transitive with possessive determiner</h>
          <p>Basic pattern – <ul>
              <li><m>Tha Raonaid air mo phògadh.</m>
                <en>Rachel has kissed me.</en></li>
            </ul>
          </p>
          <!-- WL: Not sure if it is relevant, but I hear younger speakers using perfect aspect where older, more fluent speakers would use the perfective (i.e. simple past) -->
          <p>Examples from dictionaries and grammars – <xl id="retro-possessive-dictionary">
              <li>
                <gd>Tha iad air fhaicinn. / Bha iad air am moladh.</gd>
                <tr>They have seen him. / They had praised them.</tr>
                <ref text="605">td. 11</ref>
              </li>
              <li>
                <gd>Tha e air a bhriseadh. / Tha e air a briseadh. / Tha e air mo shàbhaladh
                  a-rithist.</gd>
                <tr>He has broken him/it [masc.] / He has broken her/it [fem.] / He has saved me
                  again.</tr>
                <ref text="601">td. 22</ref>
              </li>
              <li>
                <gd>Tha mi air an dèanamh. / Bha na fèidh air a ghluasad.</gd>
                <tr>I have done them. / The deer had moved it.</tr>
                <ref text="608">td. 133</ref>
              </li>
            </xl>
          </p>
          <section id="passive">
            <h>passive</h>
            <p>When the possessive determiner agrees with the subject in person, number and gender,
              a passive-like sense is possible – <ul>
                <li><m>Tha bròg air a dèanamh.</m>
                  <en>A shoe has been made.</en></li>
                <li><m>Tha brògan air an dèanamh.</m>
                  <en>Shoes have been made.</en></li>
              </ul>
            </p>
            <!-- WL: The principal thing is that the subject of the main clause and the object of the non-finite clause share the same reference. But that’s probably too verbose for what we’re aiming at. -->
            
            <p>Examples from dictionaries and grammars – <xl id="passive-dictionary">
                <li>
                  <gd>Tha am feur air a ghearradh. / Bha an t-uisge beatha air a òl uile gu lèir. /
                    Cha robh na bàtaichean air an càradh. / Bha an càr air a ghoid. / Bha an t-àite
                    air a lìonadh le uisge.</gd>
                  <tr>The grass is [has been] cut. / The whisky was all [had all been] drunk. / The
                    boats were not [had not been] fixed. / The car was [had been] stolen. / The
                    place was [had been] filled with water.</tr>
                  <ref text="609">td. 171–2</ref>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <gd>Bha na lèintean air an dèanamh anns na h-Innsean. / Tha an litir air a
                    taidhpeadh a-nise. / Bidh aon doras air a dhùnadh. / Bha mi air mo leòn gu dona.
                    / Tha na bagaichean air an dèanamh. / Bha am bogsa air a ghluasad. / Bha sibh
                    air ur cumail a-mach.</gd>
                  <tr>The shirts have been made in the Islands. / The letter has been typed now. /
                    One door will have been closed. / I had been hurt badly. I had hurt myself
                    badly. / The bags have been made. / The box had been moved. / You had been kept
                    out.</tr>
                  <ref text="608">td. 133</ref>
                </li>
              </xl>
            </p>
            <p>Some instances are ambiguous between passive-like and active retrospective readings,
              at least in isolation – <xl id="ambiguous-dictionary">
                <li>
                  <gd>Bha iad air am moladh.</gd>
                  <tr>They had been praised. They had praised them.</tr>
                  <ref text="605">td. 11</ref>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <gd>Bha am fiadh air a mharbhadh. / An robh Niall air a bhualadh? / An robh Mòrag
                    air a taghadh?</gd>
                  <tr>The deer was [had been] killed. The deer had killed him. / Was Neil [had Neil
                    been] hit? Had Neil hit him? / Was Morag [had Morag been] (s)elected? Had Morag
                    (s)elected her?</tr>
                  <ref text="609">td. 171–2</ref>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <gd>Bha iad uile air an sàbhaladh.</gd>
                  <tr>They were all [had all been] saved. They had all saved them.</tr>
                  <ref text="601">td. 22</ref>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <gd>Bha duine air a mharbhadh.</gd>
                  <tr>A man has been killed. A man has killed him/it.</tr>
                  <ref text="608">td. 133</ref>
                </li>
              </xl>
            </p>
            <p>Examples with an explicit agent – <xl id="passive-agent-dictionary">
                <li>
                  <gd>Bha Iain air a bhualadh aca.</gd>
                  <tr>John was [had been] hit by them.</tr>
                  <ref text="609">td. 173</ref>
                </li>
              </xl>
            </p>
            <!-- WL: many folk use le today for agents today, although it would have been mainly used for instruments in the past of course -->
            
            <p>Examples from Gairm – <xl id="passive-gairm">
                <li>
                  <gd>Anns na ràithean ’s na bliadhnachan a tha air thoiseach oirnn, tha fhios gun
                    dig iomadh atharrachadh air Roinn na Gàidhlig sa’ Bh.B.C. [...] Mar a bhios
                    obair a’ Bh.B.C. a’ leudachadh anns a’ Ghaidhealtachd—agus tha fhios gun tachair
                    so leis na stéiseanan ùra a thathas a’ togail—bithidh sùil againn ri daoine ùra
                    ’s ri dòighean ùra. Bhitheadh e nàdurrach agus fallain <m>nam biodh barrachd
                      phrógraman air an deilbh</m> air a’ Ghaidhealtachd fhéin, agus <m>gum biodh
                      pàirt de ’n obair so air a chur an tairgse</m> nan Gaidheal ’s nan Gall air
                    Galldachd. [...]</gd>
                  <tr>During the seasons and the years that are ahead of us, it is known that many
                    changes will come to the Gaelic Department of the BBC. [...] As the work of the
                    BBC will be expanding in the Highlands – and it is known that this will happen
                    with the new stations that are being established – we will be expecting new
                    people and new methods. It would be natural and healthy if more programmes were
                    [had been] produced in the Highlands itself, and [if] some of this work were
                    [had been] offered to Gaels and non-Gaels in the Lowlands. [...]</tr>
                  <ref text="400-48">td. 297, ‘Air an Spiris’</ref>
                  <note>passive</note>
                </li>
              </xl>
            </p>
            <p>Biblical examples – <xl id="passive-bible">
                <li>
                  <gd>[...] Agus labhair righ na h-Eiphit re mnaibh-glùine nan Eabhruidheach [...]
                    Agus thubhairt e, ’Nuair a ni sibh gnìomh mnà-glùine do na mnaibh Eabhruidheach,
                    agus a chi sibh iad air na stòlaibh; ma’s mac a bhios ann, ’an sin marbhaidh
                    sibh e, ach ma’s nighean a bhios ann, bithidh si beo. Ach bha eagal Dé air na
                    mnaibh-glùine, agus cha d’rinn iad mar a dh’àithn righ na h-Eiphit dhoibh, ach
                    ghleidh iad a’ chlann mhac beo. Agus ghairm righ na h-Eiphit air na
                    mnaibh-glùine, agus thubhairt e riu, C’ar son a rinn sibh an ni so, agus a
                    ghleidh sibh a’ chlann mhac beo? Agus thubhairt na mnài-ghlùine re Pharaoh, A
                    chionn nach ’eil na mnài Eabhruidheach mar na mnài Eiphiteach: oir <m>tha
                      iad</m> féin beothail, agus <m>air an aisead</m> mu’n d’thig na mnài-ghlùine a
                    steach d’an ionnsuidh. Uime sin bhuin Dia gu math ris na mnaibh-glùine: agus
                    rinneadh an sluagh lìonmhor, agus dh’fhàs iad ro-chumhachdach. [...]</gd>
                  <tr>[...] And the king of Egypt spake to the Hebrew midwives [...] And he said,
                    When ye do the office of a midwife to the Hebrew women, and see them upon the
                    stools; if it be a son, then ye shall kill him: but if it be a daughter, then
                    she shall live. But the midwives feared God, and did not as the king of Egypt
                    commanded them, but saved the men children alive. And the king of Egypt called
                    for the midwives, and said unto them, Why have ye done this thing, and have
                    saved the men children alive? And the midwives said unto Pharaoh, Because the
                    Hebrew women are not as the Egyptian women; for they are lively, and are
                    delivered ere the midwives come in unto them. Therefore God dealt well with the
                    midwives: and the people multiplied, and waxed very mighty. [...]</tr>
                  <ref text="160">Ecsodus I.15–20</ref>
                </li>
              </xl>
            </p>

          </section>
        </section>
        <section id="immediate">
          <h>immediately retrospective</h>
          <!--<p>cf. <a href="?gd=dìreach"><g>dìreach</g></a></p>-->
          <p>Examples from dictionaries and grammars – <xl id="immediate-dictionary">
              <li>
                <gd>Tha Màiri dìreach air tighinn. / Tha iad dìreach air falbh. / Tha iad dìreach
                  air an doras a dhùnadh.</gd>
                <tr>Mary has just come. / They have just left. / They have just closed the
                  door.</tr>
                <ref text="609">td. 160</ref>
              </li>
            </xl>
          </p>
          <!-- WL: might be good to mention an dèidh and an dèis in this context. Lots of interesting discussion in Reed 2012: 31, 75 —  Reed, Sylvia L. 2012. The semantics of grammatical aspect: Evidence from Scottish Gaelic. Unpublished PhD. Department of Linguistics, University of Arizona. -->
        </section>
      </section>

    </section>


